WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:28.357
<v Riley>Hey, welcome back. On today's episode — a farm safety net that might be inflating ranch land prices instead of protecting producers, a new regenerative farming framework trying to fix that, and mining billionaires dropping hundreds of millions in an afternoon while agriculture can't get near that kind of capital. So who actually captures the value on working lands? That and more, coming right up.

00:00:53.657 --> 00:01:18.085
<v Riley>Welcome to Cariboo Signals, an AI-generated review of the latest tech news and ideas that impact our rural communities — I'm Riley. It's Tuesday, July 21st, 2026. Coming to you from the Cariboo, on lands that have been cared for by the Secwépemc, Tŝilhqot'in, and Dakelh peoples since time immemorial. Today's theme is Working Lands & Industry.

00:01:19.385 --> 00:01:33.099
<v Casey>And I'm Casey. We're looking at forestry, ranching, mining, and farming today — who does the work on these lands, and who ends up holding the value at the end of it.

00:01:33.399 --> 00:01:48.398
<v Riley>Quick weather check before we get into it. Out at Horsefly Lake it's already 13 degrees with clear skies, heading for a high of 27, low of 12 tonight — tomorrow looks mainly clear too.

00:01:48.698 --> 00:02:14.840
<v Casey>Across the rest of the region — 100 Mile House sitting at 13, Williams Lake at 14, Quesnel at 12, and out on the Chilcotin plateau, Riske Creek also at 13. It's a hot one region-wide, so stay hydrated, and if you're anywhere near the fire zones, check the BC Wildfire Dashboard before you head out. Let's get into the news.

00:02:16.340 --> 00:02:51.911
<v Riley>We're starting with the numbers, because they set the mood for everything else in the sector this week. The Western Producer is reporting the Canadian dollar has been strengthening against the US greenback — good news if you're an importer, but if you're a Cariboo rancher trying to sell cattle south of the border, a stronger loonie means a smaller return on every animal that crosses. Currency movements like this ripple through auction prices at yards from Williams Lake to Vanderhoof within weeks.

00:02:52.211 --> 00:02:59.068
<v Casey>So the currency story and the farm-profitability story are really the same story wearing different clothes.

00:02:59.368 --> 00:03:33.653
<v Riley>Exactly — and AgWeb picks up that profitability thread directly. They're asking whether the federal farm safety net — crop insurance, income stabilization, the whole suite of programs meant to smooth out bad years — has actually become a profit enhancer instead. The argument is that guaranteed payouts get capitalized into land prices over time, so a program built to protect farmers from disaster ends up making land more expensive for the next generation trying to get into the business.

00:03:34.453 --> 00:03:59.310
<v Casey>That's the part that should worry anyone under forty looking at Cariboo ranch land right now. If the safety net inflates the asset price, it doesn't matter how efficient your operation is — you still can't afford to buy in. The program ends up protecting the people who already own the land, not the people trying to start.

00:03:59.610 --> 00:04:28.752
<v Riley>It's not hypothetical, either. Land economists have documented this exact pattern in the US corn belt for over a decade — subsidized risk gets baked into land values faster than production income can justify. The Cariboo isn't grain country, but Crown grazing tenure and ALR ranch parcels aren't immune to the same capitalization effect. When a buyer knows the downside is covered, they'll pay more for the upside.

00:04:29.052 --> 00:04:45.766
<v Casey>Worth asking directly who benefits from that design. Established operators with land already on the books gain paper equity every year. New entrants, or someone trying to expand a small operation, get priced further out before they even start.

00:04:47.266 --> 00:05:12.980
<v Riley>Sticking with agriculture — the Western Producer also has a story on a new global regenerative farming framework that just launched here in Canada, out of a gathering near Saskatoon. It's farmer-led, which matters, but the organizer's own quote was blunt: there has to be something in it for producers, or the framework doesn't survive contact with actual farm economics.

00:05:13.280 --> 00:05:31.280
<v Casey>That's the honest version of the pitch, at least — most of these things arrive with a lot of stewardship language and not much clarity on who actually pays the certification cost, or who verifies the claims five years down the road.

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:42.722
<v Riley>We'll come back to that one — it's most of what we want to dig into in the Deep Dive today, especially against that safety-net story.

00:05:44.222 --> 00:06:17.222
<v Casey>Shifting into forestry — Ricochet published a feature on the last stands of old growth still facing active logging, with First Nations elders describing what's left as treated like collateral damage by industry. It's not a new fight in this province, but the framing here is sharper: the remaining ancient stands are small enough now that each individual cutblock decision is essentially final. There's no "next old-growth forest" waiting in reserve once these particular stands are gone.

00:06:17.522 --> 00:06:31.236
<v Riley>That's the version of working lands that never shows up in a quarterly earnings report — once it's cut, there's no regrowth cycle bringing it back in anyone's lifetime, or several lifetimes.

00:06:31.536 --> 00:07:01.535
<v Casey>And it connects to a related piece from The Narwhal — roughly five million frogs have been relocated off cutblocks and development sites across BC over the years, as a standard mitigation measure attached to permits. Nobody has actually tracked how many of them survived the move. A conservation biologist quoted in the piece put it plainly — we grew up loving frogs, then collectively stopped paying attention to them.

00:07:01.835 --> 00:07:09.977
<v Riley>So the mitigation condition exists on paper, but the monitoring that would tell you whether it's actually working doesn't.

00:07:10.277 --> 00:07:22.276
<v Casey>That's the recurring pattern with a lot of industrial permitting conditions in this province — the requirement gets written into the permit, the verification budget never follows it.

00:07:23.476 --> 00:07:53.904
<v Riley>Turning to the capital side of resource extraction — two mining stories worth pairing together. Mining billionaire Andrew Forrest just bought a seventeen percent stake in EQ Resources, an Australian tungsten producer, for around 133 million dollars, and the stock posted its biggest single-day gain on the news. Separately, Pierre Lassonde's new venture, Cadillac Mines, is targeting an IPO of up to 363 million dollars, with Agnico Eagle among the backers.

00:07:54.204 --> 00:08:10.489
<v Casey>Big capital moving fast into critical minerals in the same week a farm story is asking whether producers can even hold onto their land. Different resource sectors, same imbalance in who has access to that kind of money.

00:08:10.789 --> 00:08:18.931
<v Riley>We'll pick that comparison back up in the Deep Dive — it's actually central to the value-capture question today.

00:08:20.131 --> 00:08:52.702
<v Casey>And BC's government has launched a public consultation on improving the natural resource appeals process — the system operators and communities use to challenge or defend permitting decisions. We got into a related question a while back on biodiversity monitoring infrastructure and who gets to see resource decision data before it's finalized. This is a narrower piece, just the appeals mechanism itself, so we won't re-tread that whole conversation, but it's the same institutional machinery underneath.

00:08:54.202 --> 00:09:28.916
<v Riley>On the currency and trade front, TechRadar has an item that's worth a mention even though it's off our usual beat — Ukraine claims a 400-dollar FPV drone destroyed a Russian Mi-28 attack helicopter valued around 19 million dollars. It's not a Cariboo story directly, but it's a striking data point on how cheap consumer hardware can upend an asset built on old economics — a theme that shows up in resource industries too, when new tools change who can compete.

00:09:29.216 --> 00:09:36.073
<v Casey>Different battlefield, same lesson — cheap tech doesn't always favor the incumbent with the expensive equipment.

00:09:36.373 --> 00:09:50.515
<v Riley>Also worth noting today — the Quesnel Cariboo Observer has photos up from the fiftieth Billy Barker Days parade, which by the sound of it drew a big crowd downtown over the weekend.

00:09:50.815 --> 00:09:55.100
<v Casey>Fifty years is a good run for a small-town parade.

00:09:55.400 --> 00:10:09.114
<v Riley>100 Mile House's Hot July Nights car show pulled in more than 500 registered vehicles this year, according to the Free Press — organizers called it a record turnout for the event.

00:10:09.414 --> 00:10:14.128
<v Casey>Good excuse to get outside before the smoke rolls back in.

00:10:14.428 --> 00:10:24.713
<v Riley>On the political front, former BC Liberal cabinet minister Mike Bernier has been introduced in Victoria as the new leader of the CentreBC party.

00:10:25.013 --> 00:10:34.013
<v Casey>We'll keep an eye on where that party lands on resource and land-use policy specifically, since that's squarely in our lane.

00:10:34.313 --> 00:10:46.741
<v Riley>And BC Wildfire Service is currently managing close to a dozen active fires across the Cariboo region, including one near Clinton that prompted an evacuation of a provincial park.

00:10:47.541 --> 00:10:56.541
<v Casey>If you're anywhere near Clinton or the Pear Lake area, check directly with BC Wildfire rather than relying on secondhand information.

00:10:56.841 --> 00:11:10.555
<v Riley>One more before we move on — the USDA down in the US announced a sweeping overhaul of its National Agricultural Statistics Service, following controversy over the accuracy of its acreage reporting.

00:11:10.855 --> 00:11:26.283
<v Casey>Bad crop data isn't just a bureaucratic embarrassment — it feeds directly into commodity price swings that Canadian producers sell into as well, so an American statistical fumble shows up in a Cariboo rancher's cheque eventually.

00:11:26.583 --> 00:11:33.011
<v Riley>That's the roundup for today. Let's talk about who our community's supporting in the meantime.

00:11:33.311 --> 00:12:03.739
<v Casey>Today's spotlight is on the Cariboo Agricultural Research Alliance — a regional group doing applied agricultural research specifically for Cariboo farmers and ranchers. They test what actually works on our soils, our grasses, our short growing season, rather than importing recommendations built for the Fraser Valley or the Prairies. If you're running an operation up here, their trial results are built for your conditions, not someone else's. Find them at cariboo-agricultural-research.ca.

00:12:04.039 --> 00:12:16.467
<v Riley>That kind of locally-calibrated data is exactly what's missing from a lot of the national frameworks we just talked about — genuinely good to know it exists here already.

00:12:16.767 --> 00:12:21.052
<v Casey>Which is a decent way into where we're headed next.

00:12:21.352 --> 00:12:51.780
<v Riley>The AgWeb piece on the farm safety net raises a question worth sitting with for the rest of this segment. If a program meant to protect producers from bad years is actually inflating land values and rewarding people who already own land, what does a regenerative agriculture framework — something farmer-led, market-facing, tied to actual practice change — do differently? Or does it just repeat the same failure with greener branding?

00:12:52.080 --> 00:13:04.508
<v Casey>The honest answer right now is: maybe nothing, if nobody solves who pays for verification. A framework with no enforcement mechanism is just a marketing claim with extra steps.

00:13:05.308 --> 00:13:40.022
<v Riley>Except there's a structural difference worth naming. A safety net payment goes out regardless of practice — you collect whether you're doing anything differently or not, as long as you own the land and file the paperwork. A regenerative framework, built correctly, ties the payment to documented, ongoing practice change. That's a fundamentally different incentive. It rewards the rancher doing rotational grazing and building soil organic matter, not just the rancher who owns the most acres and has the best accountant.

00:13:40.322 --> 00:13:57.036
<v Casey>In theory. The organizer quoted in that piece said explicitly there has to be something in it for producers — which is an admission that right now, there isn't. You don't say that about a program that's already working.

00:13:57.336 --> 00:14:17.050
<v Riley>It's early-stage, sure. But early isn't the same as absent. Carbon markets tied to improved grazing management are already operating commercially in Alberta and Saskatchewan — verified protocols, registered credits, real buyers. The direction of travel is toward exactly the kind of practice-based payment we're describing.

00:14:17.350 --> 00:14:48.207
<v Casey>And who does the measuring, on the ground, in the Cariboo specifically? Soil carbon verification requires either expensive lab sampling or remote sensing infrastructure that assumes reliable satellite coverage and someone locally who can interpret the output. A rancher running cattle on Crown range near Riske Creek doesn't have an extension agent to call about that anymore — BC gutted a lot of that support years back, and it never came back.

00:14:48.507 --> 00:15:10.364
<v Riley>That's real, but it's also a narrower problem than it sounds. Alberta's soil carbon offset protocols use standardized sampling kits that don't require a PhD to administer — a producer association trains a handful of people regionally, and those people cover a whole district rather than needing one specialist per ranch.

00:15:10.664 --> 00:15:26.092
<v Casey>Which producer association, though? Name it. The Cariboo doesn't have the member density that Alberta's cattle sector has to spread that training cost across. You need enough dues-paying members to justify hiring even one shared technician.

00:15:26.892 --> 00:15:47.034
<v Riley>That's the actual constraint worth naming precisely — not whether the framework concept works, but whether the Cariboo has enough registered producers to make shared verification infrastructure viable on a per-capita basis. That's a genuinely open question, and it's different from saying the tool itself is broken.

00:15:47.334 --> 00:16:06.619
<v Casey>Open question, sure, but it changes the entire calculus of whether this is realistic here versus somewhere with tighter producer density. A model that pencils out in southern Alberta doesn't automatically pencil out for ranches scattered across the Chilcotin plateau with fifty kilometres between neighbours.

00:16:06.919 --> 00:16:29.633
<v Riley>Which is exactly why the Cariboo Agricultural Research Alliance matters more here than it would somewhere with existing extension infrastructure already in place. If they're running trials calibrated to our soils and grass species, they're the closest thing this region has to a shared verification backbone that a regenerative framework would actually need.

00:16:29.933 --> 00:16:47.075
<v Casey>If they're resourced to do that work at scale — running a certification program is a different animal from running single-farm demonstration plots. One is research. The other is an ongoing accountability function with legal and financial weight behind it.

00:16:48.275 --> 00:17:19.989
<v Riley>Step back to the mining stories for a second, because they sharpen the contrast by comparison. Andrew Forrest moved 133 million dollars into a tungsten stake in an afternoon. Pierre Lassonde is raising 363 million for a mining IPO with major backers already lined up. That's the capital velocity available to critical minerals right now — because tungsten and gold trade in liquid global markets with valuation models investors have trusted for a century.

00:17:20.289 --> 00:17:36.146
<v Casey>And agriculture doesn't have anything close to that, because there's no equivalent liquid market for verified regenerative beef. No standardized valuation model an investor can price in an afternoon, no century of assay history to lean on.

00:17:36.446 --> 00:18:03.445
<v Riley>Which is the actual gap worth naming. Mining capital moves fast because the commodity is fungible and the verification standard already exists — assay results, resource estimates, decades of established practice everyone agrees on. Regenerative agriculture carbon credits are closer to where mining assay standards were a hundred years ago — inconsistent, regionally variable, not yet trusted enough for capital to move quickly.

00:18:03.745 --> 00:18:29.030
<v Casey>So the honest read is: the technology and the market mechanism for regenerative agriculture exist in early form, but the trust infrastructure that would let capital treat it like tungsten doesn't exist yet. That's not a small gap. That's the entire reason mining attracts investment at a scale ranching never will, regardless of how good the underlying practice is.

00:18:29.830 --> 00:18:49.972
<v Riley>It's a gap that's closing, though, not a permanent structural feature of the sector. Verified carbon standard bodies are already building grazing-specific protocols right now. The trend line is toward more standardization, not less — the same way mining assay standards eventually converged after decades of chaos.

00:18:50.272 --> 00:19:05.271
<v Casey>Direction matters less than pace, when the rancher deciding whether to change grazing practices this season needs an answer now, not in a decade once the protocol finally matures. Nobody's cash flow waits for standardization.

00:19:06.471 --> 00:19:33.899
<v Riley>There's also the land-value angle from the AgWeb piece that loops back in here directly. If the safety net inflates land prices and rewards ownership over active practice, a regenerative premium — even a modest one — could be one of the only mechanisms that rewards management over passive land-holding. That's a meaningful structural difference, even if the market for it is still thin.

00:19:34.199 --> 00:19:59.056
<v Casey>Unless the certification itself just becomes another asset that gets capitalized into land value, the same way the safety net did. If "regenerative certified" ranches start selling for more, you've built a new premium straight into the purchase price, and the next generation is right back to being priced out — just under a greener label than before.

00:19:59.856 --> 00:20:30.284
<v Riley>That's a real risk, but it assumes the certification tracks with the land title itself rather than the operator's ongoing practice. Most of the frameworks being discussed tie the premium to continuous verified management, not a one-time land designation stamped at sale — so if the next owner stops the practice, the premium stops with them. That's actually a meaningful design difference from how ALR designation or safety-net capitalization currently work.

00:20:30.584 --> 00:20:53.726
<v Casey>Meaningful if the verification is actually enforced year over year, and not just checked once at enrollment and then quietly ignored. We've watched that exact failure mode play out with other permitting conditions — a box gets checked at the start, and nobody follows up five years later to see if anything actually changed.

00:20:54.926 --> 00:21:25.783
<v Riley>Which loops directly back to the old-growth and frog relocation stories from earlier in the show. Same failure mode — a mitigation requirement gets written into a permit at the front end, and there's no ongoing verification that it's actually working on the back end. If a regenerative agriculture framework repeats that exact pattern, Casey's right that it's just a rebrand of the same underlying problem BC already has with permitting enforcement.

00:21:26.083 --> 00:21:48.368
<v Casey>The difference with frogs is nobody's paying to track them after the fact. With a regenerative premium, at least there's a market actor with a direct financial reason to keep checking — a buyer paying more for certified beef wants proof the claim is real, or their own brand takes the hit.

00:21:48.668 --> 00:22:00.667
<v Riley>That's actually the strongest case for why this could work where the mitigation-monitoring gap hasn't — self-interested verification instead of unfunded regulatory box-checking that nobody follows up on.

00:22:01.467 --> 00:22:37.038
<v Casey>Self-interested verification only holds if the buyer has real leverage to audit the claim. A large processor or a Vancouver grocery chain buying certified regenerative beef in bulk can demand documentation and walk away if it doesn't hold up. An individual Cariboo rancher selling direct to a handful of local customers doesn't have anyone auditing anything — it runs on trust, which works fine at farmers'-market scale but doesn't scale into the kind of premium market that would actually shift land-value incentives regionally.

00:22:38.238 --> 00:22:58.809
<v Riley>So the honest state of play is this — the framework logic is sound, the incentive structure genuinely differs from the safety net's flaws, but it needs either producer-association scale or a buyer large enough to demand real verification, and the Cariboo doesn't obviously have either one yet.

00:22:59.109 --> 00:23:24.394
<v Casey>Which is where a body like the Cariboo Agricultural Research Alliance could actually matter, if it moved from running trial plots toward becoming the regional verification backbone producers don't currently have access to. That's a specific, concrete role — not just demonstration acres, but a trusted third party a buyer or a carbon-credit registry would actually accept as credible.

00:23:24.694 --> 00:23:33.694
<v Riley>That's a real next step worth someone actually proposing to them directly, rather than assuming it happens on its own timeline.

00:23:34.494 --> 00:23:58.065
<v Casey>And it's worth raising at the next producer meeting whether ranchers even want that role filled locally, or whether they'd rather it stay with a national certifying body — because local verification means local accountability, but it also demands local capacity that currently doesn't exist and would need to be built from close to zero.

00:23:59.265 --> 00:24:25.836
<v Riley>Either way, the structural question worth actually investigating isn't whether the technology for measuring soil carbon or grazing outcomes works — it does, and it's improving fast. The real question is whether the Cariboo builds or borrows the institution that verifies it, because whoever owns that verification role ends up controlling who actually captures the premium at the end of the chain.

00:24:26.136 --> 00:24:42.850
<v Casey>That's the piece nobody's decided yet, and it's a governance question, not a technology question. Until someone answers it, the safety net keeps rewarding land ownership over active management, and the regenerative premium stays theoretical for producers up here.

00:24:43.650 --> 00:24:59.507
<v Riley>Fair place to leave it genuinely open. If any Cariboo ranchers, or the Research Alliance itself, want to weigh in on whether that verification role is something they'd actually take on, we'd like to hear it directly.

00:24:59.807 --> 00:25:11.806
<v Casey>Feedback at cariboo signals dot c-a — corrections, story tips, or just tell us if we're missing the on-the-ground reality of what running that verification would actually take.

00:25:12.106 --> 00:25:17.248
<v Riley>That's today's episode. Thanks for spending part of your day with us.

00:25:17.548 --> 00:25:20.547
<v Casey>Have a great rest of your day.